Halve the @yellow pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125}. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1} (stalks and all). Cut the @lemon{1/2} into wedges.

Heat a splash of @oil{a splash} in a large #saucepan{} on high heat. When hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{210%g} and season well with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Fry until browned, ~{3-5%minutes}. Stir occasionally to avoid sticking. Once browned on all sides, remove from the pan and set aside on a clean #plate{}. 

> You may want to do this in batches to avoid stewing the chicken.

Put another splash of @oil{a splash} in your now empty saucepan. Add the peppers and tomatoes. Cook until softened, about ~{5%minutes}. Stir in the garlic, @chorizo{60%g}(sliced) and @smoked paprika{1%tsp}. Cook, stirring, for ~{3%minutes}. Meanwhile fill and boil your #kettle{}.

Add the @basmati rice{150%g} to the pan along with half the parsley. Stir to make sure it is coated in oil and cook for ~{2%minutes}. Pour in the @water for the rice{350%ml} along with the @chicken stock powder{2%cubes} and stir to dissolve.

Return the chicken to the pan and bring to the boil. Reduce the heat to medium, cover with a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) and cook for ~{15%minutes}. Remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}. 

> The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooled, add a squeeze of lemon juice. Taste the rice and season with salt and pepper and more lemon juice if it needs it. Sprinkle on the remaining parsley. Put the pan on the table, topped with lemon wedges, and let everyone help themselves. Enjoy!